# title = The Wolf and His Shadow
# sent_id = perry-260-s1
# text = Λύκος πλανώμενος ποτ' ἐν ἐρήμοις τόποις, κλίνοντος ἤδη πρὸς δύσιν Ὑπερίονος, δολιχὴν ἑαυτοῦ τὴν σκιὰν ἰδὼν ἔφη· "Λέοντ' ἐγὼ δέδοικα, τηλικοῦτος ὤν; πλέθρου τ' ἔχων τὸ μῆκος, οὐ θηρῶν ἁπλῶς πάντων δυνάστης ἀθρόων γενήσομαι;"
# parallel_id = lyceum-aesop-p260/s1
# translation_lang = en
# prose_translation = A wolf wandering in deserted places, as Hyperion was already inclining toward setting, seeing his own long shadow, said: "Do I fear a lion, being so great? Having a plethron in length, shall I not simply become the ruler of all beasts together?"
# literal_translation = A wolf wandering once in deserted places, of Hyperion already inclining toward setting, long of himself the shadow having seen he said; A lion I fear, being so great? A plethron and having the length, not of beasts simply of all ruler together shall I become?
